.table-responsive
  %table(id="embargo_info_table" class="table table-bordered" )
    %thead
      %tr(class="row idb-infographic-header" )
        %th(class="col-md-4")
          %h2 CC0
          %p CC0 1.0 Universal public domain dedication
        %th(class="col-md-4" )
          %h2 CC BY
          %p Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International license
        %th(class="col-md-4")
          %h2 Other License
          %p A license.txt file must be uploaded as part of dataset.

    %tbody
      %tr(class="row" )
        %td
          %h4
            %strong Best for reuse
          %ul
            %li Lets others distribute, remix, tweak, and build upon your work without any restrictions or requirements.
        %td
          %h4
            %strong Attribution a legal requirement
          %ul
            %li Requires that others attribute you for any reuse of your data in perpetuity.
        %td
          %h4
            %strong Other CC licenses may create reuse difficulties
          %ul
            %li CC NC, CC SA, and CC ND impose restrictions that may create incompatibilities and licensing difficulties for the reuse of research data.
      %tr(class="row" )
        %td
          %h4
            %strong You can still request attribution
          %ul
            %li Doesn't let others ignore community citation practices; just doesn't legally require attribution for reuse. You can include a request for citation or other attribution information in the readme.txt file of your dataset.
        %td
          %h4
            %strong May create reuse difficulties
          %ul
            %li Can result in unwieldy accumulation of citations and authors, known as "attribution stacking".
        %td
          %h4
            %strong Custom licensing considerations
          %ul
            %li Writing a custom license requires legal expertise and non-standard licenses complicate reuse.